                        <additions><p>Note added at the end of each part in 524 AH (1120 CE). It
                                states that Jaʿfar b. ʿAbdur-Razzāq had read the parts with his
                                master Ibnuz-Zāghūni, in a mosque at Baghdad, and that others who
                                were present, and whose name he specifies, had listened to the
                                reading and the exposition, one of them correcting his own copy on
                                the occasion.</p>
                            <p>Another short note states that Ibn 'Hasan al-Khabbāz made and
                                corrected a copy in 518 AH (1124 CE).</p>
                            <p>In 573 AH (1177 CE) the manuscript was read before Abū Muḥammad
                                al-Kāfī b. ʿAbdul-Wahhāb al-Ḥanbalī, one of Ibnuz-Zāghūnī's old
                                followers. In 587 AH (1191 CE) another of Zāghūnī's disciples heard
                                these two parts read by a younger student, Abul-Ḥajjāj Yūsuf b.
                                Khalīl of Damascus who from that time down to '643 AH (1245 CE) was
                                the owner of the volume. Other similar notes of hearings and
                                readings dated 627 AH (1229 CE) to 648 AH (1250 CE) are signed by
                                the same Yūsuf b. Khalīl.</p>
                            <p>Folio 1a: note by Abu Bakr b. Muḥammad Marzubān al-Hakkārī stating
                                that he read it in 643 AH (1245 CE) under his master Yusūf b. Khalīl
                                in the "school of the Persians" (<quote>بمدرسه بني
                                العجم</quote>.</p>
                            <p>In the margin of <locus from="1b">folio 1b</locus> there is a note
                                containing allusions to the Caliph ʿUthmān.</p>
                        </additions>
